# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electrostatics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The capacitance between two conductors depends on the opposing surface area of the conductors, the distance between those conductors, and the permittivity of any dielectric material between them.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] For many dielectric materials, the permittivity, and thus the capacitance, is independent of the potential difference between the conductors and the total charge on them.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The SI unit of capacitance is the farad (symbol: F), named after the English physicist Michael Faraday.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] A 1 farad capacitor, when charged with 1 coulomb of electrical charge, has a potential difference of 1 volt between its plates.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The reciprocal of capacitance is called elastance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In discussing electrical circuits, the term *capacitance* is usually a shorthand for the mutual capacitance between two adjacent conductors, such as the two plates of a capacitor.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] However, every isolated conductor also exhibits capacitance, here called *self-capacitance*.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] It is measured by the amount of electric charge that must be added to an isolated conductor to raise its electric potential by one unit of measurement, e.g., one volt.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The reference point for this potential is a theoretical hollow conducting sphere, of infinite radius, with the conductor centered inside this sphere.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The inter-winding capacitance of a coil is sometimes called self-capacitance, but this is a different phenomenon.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] It is actually mutual capacitance between the individual turns of the coil and is a form of stray or parasitic capacitance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] This self-capacitance is an important consideration at high frequencies: it changes the impedance of the coil and gives rise to parallel resonance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In many applications this is an undesirable effect and sets an upper frequency limit for the correct operation of the circuit.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] A common form is a parallel-plate capacitor, which consists of two conductive plates insulated from each other, usually sandwiching a dielectric material.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In a parallel plate capacitor, capacitance is very nearly proportional to the surface area of the conductor plates and inversely proportional to the separation distance between the plates.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The discussion above is limited to the case of two conducting plates, although of arbitrary size and shape.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The definition $C=Q/V$ does not apply when there are more than two charged plates, or when the net charge on the two plates is non-zero.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] To handle this case, James Clerk Maxwell introduced his *coefficients of potential*.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] If three (nearly ideal) conductors are given charges $Q_{1},Q_{2},Q_{3}$ , then the voltage (actually potential) at conductor 1 is given by $V_{1}=P_{11}Q_{1}+P_{12}Q_{2}+P_{13}Q_{3},$ and similarly for the other voltages.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Hermann von Helmholtz and Sir William Thomson showed that the coefficients of potential are symmetric, so that $P_{12}=P_{21}$ , etc.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Similarly, the charge can be written in terms of voltages (actually potentials): $Q_{1}=C_{11}V_{1}+C_{12}V_{2}+C_{13}V_{3},$ The collection of coefficients $C_{ij}={\frac {\partial Q_{i}}{\partial V_{j}}}$ is known as the *capacitance matrix*,.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In open systems which are not charge neutral, so that field lines can end at infinity (which is implicitly assumed to have 0 potential in the above equations), the capacitance and elastance matrices are inverses of each other: $C^{-1}=P$ .
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In closed systems however the capacitance matrix is singular (it has a 0 eigenvalue due to charge neutrality), and so formally the elastance matrix as the inverse of the capacitance matrix is ill defined; it would require independently varying the charges.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Since no actual device holds perfectly equal and opposite charges on each of the two "plates", it is the mutual capacitance that is reported on capacitors.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The capacitance of the majority of capacitors used in electronic circuits is generally several orders of magnitude smaller than the farad.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The most common units of capacitance are the microfarad (μF), nanofarad (nF), picofarad (pF), and, in microcircuits, femtofarad (fF).
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Some applications also use supercapacitors that can be much larger, as much as hundreds of farads, and parasitic capacitive elements can be less than a femtofarad.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Historical texts use other, obsolete submultiples of the farad, such as "mf" and "mfd" for microfarad (μF); "mmf", "mmfd", "pfd", "μμF" for picofarad (pF).
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The capacitance can be calculated if the geometry of the conductors and the dielectric properties of the insulator between the conductors are known.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Capacitance is proportional to the area of overlap and inversely proportional to the separation between conducting sheets.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The closer the sheets are to each other, the greater the capacitance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] An example is the capacitance of a capacitor constructed of two parallel plates both of area ${\textstyle A}$ separated by a distance ${\textstyle d}$ .
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The equation is a good approximation if *d* is small compared to the other dimensions of the plates so that the electric field in the capacitor area is uniform, and the so-called *fringing field* around the periphery provides only a small contribution to the capacitance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Any two adjacent conductors can function as a capacitor, though the capacitance is small unless the conductors are close together for long distances or over a large area.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] This (often unwanted) capacitance is called parasitic or stray capacitance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Stray capacitance can allow signals to leak between otherwise isolated circuits (an effect called crosstalk), and it can be a limiting factor for proper functioning of circuits at high frequency.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Stray capacitance between the input and output in amplifier circuits can be troublesome because it can form a path for feedback, which can cause instability and parasitic oscillation in the amplifier.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] It is often convenient for analytical purposes to replace this capacitance with a combination of one input-to-ground capacitance and one output-to-ground capacitance; the original configuration – including the input-to-output capacitance – is often referred to as a pi-configuration.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Since impedance varies inversely with capacitance, the internode capacitance, *C*, is replaced by a capacitance of KC from input to ground and a capacitance of ⁠(*K* − 1)*C*/*K*⁠ from output to ground.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] When the input-to-output gain is very large, the equivalent input-to-ground impedance is very small while the output-to-ground impedance is essentially equal to the original (input-to-output) impedance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Calculating the capacitance of a system amounts to solving the Laplace equation ${\textstyle \nabla ^{2}\varphi =0}$ with a constant potential ${\textstyle \varphi }$ on the 2-dimensional surface of the conductors embedded in 3-space.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] There is no solution in terms of elementary functions in more complicated cases.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] For plane situations, analytic functions may be used to map different geometries to each other.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The energy (measured in joules) stored in a capacitor is equal to the *work* required to push the charges into the capacitor, i.e. to charge it.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Consider a capacitor of capacitance *C*, holding a charge +*q* on one plate and −*q* on the other.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The energy stored in a capacitor is found by integrating this equation.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The capacitance of nanoscale dielectric capacitors such as quantum dots may differ from conventional formulations of larger capacitors.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In particular, the electrostatic potential difference experienced by electrons in conventional capacitors is spatially well-defined and fixed by the shape and size of metallic electrodes in addition to the statistically large number of electrons present in conventional capacitors.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In nanoscale capacitors, however, the electrostatic potentials experienced by electrons are determined by the number and locations of all electrons that contribute to the electronic properties of the device.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In such devices, the number of electrons may be very small, so the resulting spatial distribution of equipotential surfaces within the device is exceedingly complex.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The capacitance of a connected, or "closed", single-electron device is twice the capacitance of an unconnected, or "open", single-electron device.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] whose energy terms may be obtained as solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] This expression of "quantum capacitance" may be written as $C_{Q}(N)={e^{2} \over U(N)},$ which differs from the conventional expression described in the introduction where $W_{\text{stored}}=U$ , the stored electrostatic potential energy, $C={Q^{2} \over 2U},$ by a factor of ⁠1/2⁠ with $Q=Ne$ .
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] which is appropriate since $\mathrm {d} q=0$ for systems involving either many electrons or metallic electrodes, but in few-electron systems, $\mathrm {d} q\to \Delta \,Q=e$ .
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The integral generally becomes a summation.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] One may trivially combine the expressions of capacitance $Q=CV$ and electrostatic interaction energy, $U=QV,$ to obtain $C=Q{1 \over V}=Q{Q \over U}={Q^{2} \over U},$ which is similar to the quantum capacitance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] A more rigorous derivation is reported in the literature.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In particular, to circumvent the mathematical challenges of spatially complex equipotential surfaces within the device, an *average* electrostatic potential experienced by each electron is utilized in the derivation.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Apparent mathematical differences may be understood more fundamentally.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The potential energy, $U(N)$ , of an isolated device (self-capacitance) is twice that stored in a "connected" device in the lower limit $N=1$ .
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In nanoscale devices such as quantum dots, the "capacitor" is often an isolated or partially isolated component within the device.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] The primary differences between nanoscale capacitors and macroscopic (conventional) capacitors are the number of excess electrons (charge carriers, or electrons, that contribute to the device's electronic behavior) and the shape and size of metallic electrodes.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In nanoscale devices, nanowires consisting of metal atoms typically do not exhibit the same conductive properties as their macroscopic, or bulk material, counterparts.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In electronic and semiconductor devices, transient or frequency-dependent current between terminals contains both conduction and displacement components.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Conduction current is related to moving charge carriers (electrons, holes, ions, etc.), while displacement current is caused by a time-varying electric field.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Carrier transport is affected by electric fields and by a number of physical phenomena - such as carrier drift and diffusion, trapping, injection, contact-related effects, impact ionization, etc.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] As a result, device admittance is frequency-dependent, and a simple electrostatic formula for capacitance $C=q/V,$ is not applicable.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] A more general definition of capacitance, encompassing electrostatic formula, is: $C={\frac {\operatorname {Im} (Y(\omega ))}{\omega }},$ where $Y(\omega )$ is the device admittance, and $\omega$ is the angular frequency.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] In general, capacitance is a function of frequency.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] At high frequencies, capacitance approaches a constant value, equal to "geometric" capacitance, determined by the terminals' geometry and dielectric content in the device.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] A paper by Steven Laux presents a review of numerical techniques for capacitance calculation.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Usually, capacitance in semiconductor devices is positive.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] However, in some devices and under certain conditions (temperature, applied voltages, frequency, etc.), capacitance can become negative.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Non-monotonic behavior of the transient current in response to a step-like excitation has been proposed as the mechanism of negative capacitance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Negative capacitance has been demonstrated and explored in many different types of semiconductor devices.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] A capacitance meter is a piece of electronic test equipment used to measure capacitance, mainly of discrete capacitors.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] For most purposes and in most cases the capacitor must be disconnected from circuit.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Many DVMs (digital volt meters) have a capacitance-measuring function.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] These usually operate by charging and discharging the capacitor under test with a known current and measuring the rate of rise of the resulting voltage; the slower the rate of rise, the larger the capacitance.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] DVMs can usually measure capacitance from nanofarads to a few hundred microfarads, but wider ranges are not unusual.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] It is also possible to measure capacitance by passing a known high-frequency alternating current through the device under test and measuring the resulting voltage across it (does not work for polarised capacitors).
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] More sophisticated instruments use other techniques such as inserting the capacitor-under-test into a bridge circuit.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] By varying the values of the other legs in the bridge (so as to bring the bridge into balance), the value of the unknown capacitor is determined.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] This method of *indirect* use of measuring capacitance ensures greater precision.
[src:electrostatics/capacitance] Through the use of Kelvin connections and other careful design techniques, these instruments can usually measure capacitors over a range from picofarads to farads.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In an isolated system, the total charge stays the same - the amount of positive charge minus the amount of negative charge does not change over time.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Electric charge carriers include subatomic particles.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In ordinary matter, negative charge is carried by electrons, and positive charge is carried by the protons in the nuclei of atoms.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] If there are more electrons than protons in a piece of matter, it will have a negative charge, if there are fewer it will have a positive charge, and if there are equal numbers it will be neutral.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Charge is *quantized*: it comes in integer multiples of individual small units called the elementary charge, *e*, about 1.602×10−19 C, which is the smallest charge that can exist freely.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Particles called quarks have smaller charges, multiples of ⁠1/3⁠*e*, but they are found only combined in particles that have a charge that is an integer multiple of *e*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In the Standard Model, charge is an absolutely conserved quantum number.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The proton has a charge of +*e*, and the electron has a charge of −*e*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Today, a negative charge is defined as the charge carried by an electron and a positive charge is that carried by a proton.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Before these particles were discovered, a positive charge was defined by Benjamin Franklin as the charge acquired by a glass rod when it is rubbed with a silk cloth.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Electric charges produce electric fields.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] A moving charge also produces a magnetic field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The interaction of electric charges with an electromagnetic field (a combination of an electric and a magnetic field) is the source of the electromagnetic (or Lorentz) force, which is one of the four fundamental interactions in physics.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The study of photon-mediated interactions among charged particles is called quantum electrodynamics.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The SI derived unit of electric charge is the coulomb (C) named after French physicist Charles-Augustin de Coulomb.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In electrical engineering it is also common to use the ampere-hour (A⋅h).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In physics and chemistry it is common to use the elementary charge (*e*) as a unit.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Chemistry also uses the Faraday constant, which is the charge of one mole of elementary charges.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Charge is the fundamental property of matter that exhibits electrostatic attraction or repulsion in the presence of other matter with charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Electric charge is a characteristic property of many subatomic particles.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The charges of free-standing particles are integer multiples of the elementary charge *e*; we say that electric charge is *quantized*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Michael Faraday, in his electrolysis experiments, was the first to note the discrete nature of electric charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Robert Millikan's oil drop experiment demonstrated this fact directly, and measured the elementary charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] It has been discovered that one type of particle, quarks, have fractional charges of either −⁠1/3⁠ or +⁠2/3⁠, but it is believed they always occur in multiples of integral charge; free-standing quarks have never been observed.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] By convention, the charge of an electron is negative, *−e*, while that of a proton is positive, *+e*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Charged particles whose charges have the same sign repel one another, and particles whose charges have different signs attract.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Coulomb's law quantifies the electrostatic force between two particles by asserting that the force is proportional to the product of their charges, and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The charge of an antiparticle equals that of the corresponding particle, but with opposite sign.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The electric charge of a macroscopic object is the sum of the electric charges of the particles that it is made up of.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This charge is often small, because matter is made of atoms, and atoms typically have equal numbers of protons and electrons, in which case their charges cancel out, yielding a net charge of zero, thus making the atom neutral.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] An *ion* is an atom (or group of atoms) that has lost one or more electrons, giving it a net positive charge (cation), or that has gained one or more electrons, giving it a net negative charge (anion).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] *Monatomic ions* are formed from single atoms, while *polyatomic ions* are formed from two or more atoms that have been bonded together, in each case yielding an ion with a positive or negative net charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Electric field induced by a positive electric charge (left) and a field induced by a negative electric charge (right).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] During the formation of macroscopic objects, constituent atoms and ions usually combine to form structures composed of neutral *ionic compounds* electrically bound to neutral atoms.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Thus macroscopic objects tend toward being neutral overall, but macroscopic objects are rarely perfectly net neutral.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Sometimes macroscopic objects contain ions distributed throughout the material, rigidly bound in place, giving an overall net positive or negative charge to the object.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Also, macroscopic objects made of conductive elements can more or less easily (depending on the element) take on or give off electrons, and then maintain a net negative or positive charge indefinitely.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] When the net electric charge of an object is non-zero and motionless, the phenomenon is known as static electricity.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This can easily be produced by rubbing two dissimilar materials together, such as rubbing amber with fur or glass with silk.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In this way, non-conductive materials can be charged to a significant degree, either positively or negatively.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Charge taken from one material is moved to the other material, leaving an opposite charge of the same magnitude behind.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The law of *conservation of charge* always applies, giving the object from which a negative charge is taken a positive charge of the same magnitude, and vice versa.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Even when an object's net charge is zero, the charge can be distributed non-uniformly in the object (e.g., due to an external electromagnetic field, or bound polar molecules).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In such cases, the object is said to be polarized.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The charge due to polarization is known as bound charge, while the charge on an object produced by electrons gained or lost from outside the object is called *free charge*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The motion of electrons in conductive metals in a specific direction is known as electric current.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The SI unit of quantity of electric charge is the coulomb (symbol: C).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The coulomb is defined as the quantity of charge that passes through the cross section of an electrical conductor carrying one ampere for one second.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This unit was proposed in 1946 and ratified in 1948.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The lowercase symbol *q* is often used to denote a quantity of electric charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The quantity of electric charge can be directly measured with an electrometer, or indirectly measured with a ballistic galvanometer.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The elementary charge is defined as a fundamental constant in the SI.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The value for elementary charge, when expressed in SI units, is exactly 1.602176634×10−19 C.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] After discovering the quantized character of charge, in 1891, George Stoney proposed the unit 'electron' for this fundamental unit of electrical charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Thomson subsequently discovered the particle that we now call the electron in 1897.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The unit is today referred to as *elementary charge*, *fundamental unit of charge*, or simply denoted *e*, with the charge of an electron being −*e*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The charge of an isolated system should be a multiple of the elementary charge *e*, even if at large scales charge seems to behave as a continuous quantity.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In some contexts it is meaningful to speak of fractions of an elementary charge; for example, in the fractional quantum Hall effect.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The unit faraday is sometimes used in electrochemistry.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] One faraday is the magnitude of the charge of one mole of elementary charges, i.e.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] From ancient times, people were familiar with four types of phenomena that today would all be explained using the concept of electric charge: (a) lightning, (b) the torpedo fish (or electric ray), (c) St Elmo's Fire, and (d) that amber rubbed with fur would attract small, light objects.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The first account of the *amber effect* is often attributed to the ancient Greek mathematician Thales of Miletus, who lived from c.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] 546 BC, but there are doubts about whether Thales left any writings; his account about amber is known from an account from early 200s.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This account can be taken as evidence that the phenomenon was known since at least c.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] 600 BC, but Thales explained this phenomenon as evidence for inanimate objects having a soul.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In other words, there was no indication of any conception of electric charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] More generally, the ancient Greeks did not understand the connections among these four kinds of phenomena.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The Greeks observed that the charged amber buttons could attract light objects such as hair.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] They also found that if they rubbed the amber for long enough, they could even get an electric spark to jump, but there is also a claim that no mention of electric sparks appeared until late 17th century.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This property derives from the triboelectric effect.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In late 1100s, the substance jet, a compacted form of coal, was noted to have an amber effect, and in the middle of the 1500s, Girolamo Fracastoro, discovered that diamond also showed this effect.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Some efforts were made by Fracastoro and others, especially Gerolamo Cardano to develop explanations for this phenomenon.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In contrast to astronomy, mechanics, and optics, which had been studied quantitatively since antiquity, the start of ongoing qualitative and quantitative research into electrical phenomena can be marked with the publication of *De Magnete* by the English scientist William Gilbert in 1600.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In this book, there was a small section where Gilbert returned to the amber effect (as he called it) in addressing many of the earlier theories, and coined the Neo-Latin word *electrica* (from ἤλεκτρον (ēlektron), the Greek word for *amber*).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The Latin word was translated into English as *electrics*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Gilbert is also credited with the term *electrical*, while the term *electricity* came later, first attributed to Sir Thomas Browne in his Pseudodoxia Epidemica from 1646.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] (For more linguistic details see Etymology of electricity.) Gilbert hypothesized that this amber effect could be explained by an effluvium (a small stream of particles that flows from the electric object, without diminishing its bulk or weight) that acts on other objects.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This idea of a material electrical effluvium was influential in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] It was a precursor to ideas developed in the 18th century about "electric fluid" (Dufay, Nollet, Franklin) and "electric charge".
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Around 1663 Otto von Guericke invented what was probably the first electrostatic generator, but he did not recognize it primarily as an electrical device and only conducted minimal electrical experiments with it.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Other European pioneers were Robert Boyle, who in 1675 published the first book in English that was devoted solely to electrical phenomena.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] His work was largely a repetition of Gilbert's studies, but he also identified several more "electrics", and noted mutual attraction between two bodies.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In 1729 Stephen Gray was experimenting with static electricity, which he generated using a glass tube.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He noticed that a cork, used to protect the tube from dust and moisture, also became electrified (charged).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Further experiments (e.g., extending the cork by putting thin sticks into it) showed—for the first time—that electrical effluvia (as Gray called it) could be transmitted (conducted) over a distance.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Gray managed to transmit charge with twine (765 feet) and wire (865 feet).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Through these experiments, Gray discovered the importance of different materials, which facilitated or hindered the conduction of electrical effluvia.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] John Theophilus Desaguliers, who repeated many of Gray's experiments, is credited with coining the terms conductors and insulators to refer to the effects of different materials in these experiments.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Gray also discovered electrical induction (i.e., where charge could be transmitted from one object to another without any direct physical contact).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] For example, he showed that by bringing a charged glass tube close to, but not touching, a lump of lead that was sustained by a thread, it was possible to make the lead become electrified (e.g., to attract and repel brass filings).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He attempted to explain this phenomenon with the idea of electrical effluvia.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Gray's discoveries introduced an important shift in the historical development of knowledge about electric charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The fact that electrical effluvia could be transferred from one object to another, opened the theoretical possibility that this property was not inseparably connected to the bodies that were electrified by rubbing.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] When glass was rubbed with silk, du Fay said that the glass was charged with *vitreous electricity*, and, when amber was rubbed with fur, the amber was charged with *resinous electricity*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In contemporary understanding, positive charge is now defined as the charge of a glass rod after being rubbed with a silk cloth, but it is arbitrary which type of charge is called positive and which is called negative.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Another important two-fluid theory from this time was proposed by Jean-Antoine Nollet (1745).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Up until about 1745, the main explanation for electrical attraction and repulsion was the idea that electrified bodies gave off an effluvium.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Benjamin Franklin started electrical experiments in late 1746, and by 1750 had developed a one-fluid theory of electricity, based on an experiment that showed that a rubbed glass received the same, but opposite, charge strength as the cloth used to rub the glass.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Franklin imagined electricity as being a type of invisible fluid present in all matter and coined the term *charge* itself (as well as battery and some others); for example, he believed that it was the glass in a Leyden jar that held the accumulated charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He posited that rubbing insulating surfaces together caused this fluid to change location, and that a flow of this fluid constitutes an electric current.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He also posited that when matter contained an excess of the fluid it was *positively* charged and when it had a deficit it was *negatively* charged.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He identified the term *positive* with vitreous electricity and *negative* with resinous electricity after performing an experiment with a glass tube he had received from his overseas colleague Peter Collinson.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The experiment had participant A charge the glass tube and participant B receive a shock to the knuckle from the charged tube.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Franklin identified participant B to be positively charged after having been shocked by the tube.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] There is some ambiguity about whether William Watson independently arrived at the same one-fluid explanation around the same time (1747).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Watson, after seeing Franklin's letter to Collinson, claims that he had presented the same explanation as Franklin in spring 1747.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Franklin had studied some of Watson's works prior to making his own experiments and analysis, which was probably significant for Franklin's own theorizing.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] One physicist suggests that Watson first proposed a one-fluid theory, which Franklin then elaborated further and more influentially.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] A historian of science argues that Watson missed a subtle difference between his ideas and Franklin's, so that Watson misinterpreted his ideas as being similar to Franklin's.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In any case, there was no animosity between Watson and Franklin, and the Franklin model of electrical action, formulated in early 1747, eventually became widely accepted at that time.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] After Franklin's work, effluvia-based explanations were rarely put forward.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] It is now known that the Franklin model was fundamentally correct.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] There is only one kind of electrical charge, and only one variable is required to keep track of the amount of charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Until 1800 it was only possible to study conduction of electric charge by using an electrostatic discharge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In 1800 Alessandro Volta was the first to show that charge could be maintained in continuous motion through a closed path.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In 1833, Michael Faraday sought to remove any doubt that electricity is identical, regardless of the source by which it is produced.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He discussed a variety of known forms, which he characterized as common electricity (e.g., static electricity, piezoelectricity, magnetic induction), voltaic electricity (e.g., electric current from a voltaic pile), and animal electricity (e.g., bioelectricity).
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In 1838, Faraday raised a question about whether electricity was a fluid or fluids or a property of matter, like gravity.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He investigated whether matter could be charged with one kind of charge independently of the other.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He came to the conclusion that electric charge was a relation between two or more bodies, because he could not charge one body without having an opposite charge in another body.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In 1838, Faraday also put forth a theoretical explanation of electric force, while expressing neutrality about whether it originates from one, two, or no fluids.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] He focused on the idea that the normal state of particles is to be nonpolarized, and that when polarized, they seek to return to their natural, nonpolarized state.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In developing a field theory approach to electrodynamics (starting in the mid-1850s), James Clerk Maxwell stops considering electric charge as a special substance that accumulates in objects, and starts to understand electric charge as a consequence of the transformation of energy in the field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This pre-quantum understanding considered magnitude of electric charge to be a continuous quantity, even at the microscopic level.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Static electricity refers to the electric charge of an object and the related electrostatic discharge when two objects are brought together that are not at equilibrium.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] An electrostatic discharge creates a change in the charge of each of the two objects.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] When a piece of glass and a piece of resin—neither of which exhibit any electrical properties—are rubbed together and left with the rubbed surfaces in contact, they still exhibit no electrical properties.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] When separated, they attract each other.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This attraction and repulsion is an *electrical phenomenon*, and the bodies that exhibit them are said to be *electrified*, or *electrically charged*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Bodies may be electrified in many other ways, as well as by sliding.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The electrical properties of the two pieces of glass are similar to each other but opposite to those of the two pieces of resin: The glass attracts what the resin repels and repels what the resin attracts.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] If a body electrified in any manner whatsoever behaves as the glass does, that is, if it repels the glass and attracts the resin, the body is said to be *vitreously* electrified, and if it attracts the glass and repels the resin it is said to be *resinously* electrified.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] All electrified bodies are either vitreously or resinously electrified.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] An established convention in the scientific community defines vitreous electrification as positive, and resinous electrification as negative.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Electric current is the flow of electric charge through an object.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The most common charge carriers are the positively charged proton and the negatively charged electron.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The movement of any of these charged particles constitutes an electric current.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] In many situations, it suffices to speak of the *conventional current* without regard to whether it is carried by positive charges moving in the direction of the conventional current or by negative charges moving in the opposite direction.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This macroscopic viewpoint is an approximation that simplifies electromagnetic concepts and calculations.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The direction of the conventional current in most metallic wires is opposite to the drift velocity of the actual charge carriers; i.e., the electrons.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The total electric charge of an isolated system remains constant regardless of changes within the system itself.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This law is inherent to all processes known to physics and can be derived in a local form from gauge invariance of the wave function.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] The conservation of charge results in the charge-current continuity equation.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] where *I* is the net outward current through a closed surface and *q* is the electric charge contained within the volume defined by the surface.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] Aside from the properties described in articles about electromagnetism, electric charge is a relativistic invariant.
[src:electrostatics/electric-charge] This means that any particle that has electric charge *q* has the same electric charge regardless of how fast it is travelling.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The **electric dipole moment** is a measure of the separation of positive and negative electrical charges within a system: that is, a measure of the system's overall polarity.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The SI unit for electric dipole moment is the coulomb-metre (C⋅m).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The debye (D) is a CGS unit of measurement used in atomic physics and chemistry.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Theoretically, an electric dipole is defined by the first-order term of the multipole expansion; it consists of two equal and opposite charges that are infinitesimally close together, although real dipoles have separated charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipole consists of two point electric charges of opposite polarity located close together.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A transformation from a point-shaped dipole to a finite-size electric dipole is shown.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] is polar because of the unequal sharing of its electrons in a "bent" structure.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A separation of charge is present with negative charge in the middle (red shade), and positive charge at the ends (blue shade).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Often in physics, the dimensions of an object can be ignored so it can be treated as a point-like object, i.e. a point particle.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Point particles with electric charge are referred to as point charges.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Two point charges, one with charge +*q* and the other one with charge −*q* separated by a distance d, constitute an ***electric dipole*** (a simple case of an electric multipole).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For this case, the electric dipole moment has a magnitude $p=qd$ and is directed from the negative charge to the positive one.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The electric dipole moment vector **p** also points from the negative charge to the positive charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] With this definition the dipole direction tends to align itself with an external electric field (and note that the electric flux lines produced by the charges of the dipole itself, which point from positive charge to negative charge, then tend to oppose the flux lines of the external field).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Note that this sign convention is used in physics, while the opposite sign convention for the dipole, from the positive charge to the negative charge, is used in chemistry.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] An idealization of this two-charge system is the electrical point dipole consisting of two (infinite) charges only infinitesimally separated, but with a finite **p**.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This quantity is used in the definition of polarization density.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] An object with an electric dipole moment **p** is subject to a torque *τ* when placed in an external electric field **E**.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The torque tends to align the dipole with the field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A dipole aligned parallel to an electric field has lower potential energy than a dipole making some non-zero angle with it.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The scalar dot "⋅" product and the negative sign shows the potential energy minimizes when the dipole is parallel with the field, maximizes when it is antiparallel, and is zero when it is perpendicular.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The symbol "×" refers to the vector cross product.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The E-field vector and the dipole vector define a plane, and the torque is directed normal to that plane with the direction given by the right-hand rule.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A dipole in such a uniform field may twist and oscillate, but receives no overall net force with no linear acceleration of the dipole.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipole twists to align with the external field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] However, in a non-uniform electric field a dipole may indeed receive a net force since the force on one end of the dipole no longer balances that on the other end.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] It can be shown that this net force is generally parallel to the dipole moment.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For an array of point charges, the charge density becomes a sum of Dirac delta functions: $\rho (\mathbf {r} )=\sum _{i=1}^{N}\,q_{i}\,\delta \left(\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{i}\right),$ where each **r***i* is a vector from some reference point to the charge *qi*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This expression is equivalent to the previous expression in the case of charge neutrality and *N* = 2.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipole moment is particularly useful in the context of an overall neutral system of charges, such as a pair of opposite charges or a neutral conductor in a uniform electric field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This is the vector sum of the individual dipole moments of the neutral charge pairs.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] (Because of overall charge neutrality, the dipole moment is independent of the observer's position **r**.) Thus, the value of **p** is independent of the choice of reference point, provided the overall charge of the system is zero.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] When discussing the dipole moment of a non-neutral system, such as the dipole moment of the proton, a dependence on the choice of reference point arises.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In such cases it is conventional to choose the reference point to be the center of mass of the system, not some arbitrary origin.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This choice is not only a matter of convention: the notion of dipole moment is essentially derived from the mechanical notion of torque, and as in mechanics, it is computationally and theoretically useful to choose the center of mass as the observation point.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For a charged molecule the center of charge should be the reference point instead of the center of mass.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For neutral systems the reference point is not important, and the dipole moment is an intrinsic property of the system.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] An ideal dipole consists of two opposite charges with infinitesimal separation.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] We compute the potential and field of such an ideal dipole starting with two opposite charges at separation *d* > 0, and taking the limit as *d* → 0.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The result for the dipole potential also can be expressed as: $V(\mathbf {R} )\approx -\mathbf {p} \cdot \mathbf {\nabla } {\frac {1}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}R}}\,,$ which relates the dipole potential to that of a point charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A key point is that the potential of the dipole falls off faster with distance *R* than that of the point charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Thus, although two closely spaced opposite charges are *not quite* an ideal electric dipole (because their potential at short distances is not that of a dipole), at distances much larger than their separation, their dipole moment **p** appears directly in their potential and field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] As *d* is made infinitesimal, thus, the dipole charge must be made to increase to hold **p** constant.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This limiting process results in a "point dipole".
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipole moment of an array of charges, $\mathbf {p} =\sum _{i=1}^{N}q_{i}\mathbf {d} _{i}\,,$ determines the degree of polarity of the array, but for a neutral array it is simply a vector property of the array with no information about the array's absolute location.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipole moment *density* of the array **p**(**r**) contains both the location of the array and its dipole moment.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] When it comes time to calculate the electric field in some region containing the array, Maxwell's equations are solved, and the information about the charge array is contained in the *polarization density* **P**(**r**) of Maxwell's equations.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Depending upon how fine-grained an assessment of the electric field is required, more or less information about the charge array will have to be expressed by **P**(**r**).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] As explained below, sometimes it is sufficiently accurate to take **P**(**r**) = **p**(**r**).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Sometimes a more detailed description is needed (for example, supplementing the dipole moment density with an additional quadrupole density) and sometimes even more elaborate versions of **P**(**r**) are necessary.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Only static situations are considered in what follows, so **P**(**r**) has no time dependence, and there is no displacement current.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] First is some discussion of the polarization density **P**(**r**).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] That discussion is followed with several particular examples.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A formulation of Maxwell's equations based upon division of charges and currents into "free" and "bound" charges and currents leads to introduction of the **D**- and **P**-fields: $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon _{0}\mathbf {E} +\mathbf {P} \,,$ where **P** is called the polarization density.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Satisfaction of the boundary conditions upon *φ* may be divided arbitrarily between *φ*f and *φ*b because only the sum *φ* must satisfy these conditions.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] It follows that **P** is simply proportional to the electric field due to the charges selected as bound, with boundary conditions that prove convenient.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In particular, when *no* free charge is present, one possible choice is **P** = *ε*0 **E**.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Next is discussed how several different dipole moment descriptions of a medium relate to the polarization entering Maxwell's equations.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] As described next, a model for polarization moment density **p**(**r**) results in a polarization $\mathbf {P} (\mathbf {r} )=\mathbf {p} (\mathbf {r} )$ restricted to the same model.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For a smoothly varying dipole moment distribution **p**(**r**), the corresponding bound charge density is simply $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {p} (\mathbf {r} )=-\rho _{\text{b}},$ as we will establish shortly via integration by parts.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] However, if **p**(**r**) exhibits an abrupt step in dipole moment at a boundary between two regions, ∇·**p**(**r**) results in a surface charge component of bound charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This surface charge can be treated through a surface integral, or by using discontinuity conditions at the boundary, as illustrated in the various examples below.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] As a first example relating dipole moment to polarization, consider a medium made up of a continuous charge density *ρ*(**r**) and a continuous dipole moment distribution **p**(**r**).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The first term can be transformed to an integral over the surface bounding the volume of integration, and contributes a surface charge density, discussed later.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In short, the dipole moment density **p**(**r**) plays the role of the polarization density **P** for this medium.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Notice, **p**(**r**) has a non-zero divergence equal to the bound charge density (as modeled in this approximation).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] It may be noted that this approach can be extended to include all the multipoles: dipole, quadrupole, etc.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Using the relation: $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {D} =\rho _{\text{f}}\,,$ the polarization density is found to be: $\mathbf {P} (\mathbf {r} )=\mathbf {p} _{\text{dip}}-\nabla \cdot \mathbf {p} _{\text{quad}}+\cdots \,,$ where the added terms are meant to indicate contributions from higher multipoles.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Evidently, inclusion of higher multipoles signifies that the polarization density **P** no longer is determined by a dipole moment density **p** alone.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For example, in considering scattering from a charge array, different multipoles scatter an electromagnetic wave differently and independently, requiring a representation of the charges that goes beyond the dipole approximation.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Above, discussion was deferred for the first term in the expression for the potential due to the dipoles.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Integrating the divergence results in a surface charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The figure at the right provides an intuitive idea of why a surface charge arises.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The figure shows a uniform array of identical dipoles between two surfaces.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Internally, the heads and tails of dipoles are adjacent and cancel.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] At the bounding surfaces, however, no cancellation occurs.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Instead, on one surface the dipole heads create a positive surface charge, while at the opposite surface the dipole tails create a negative surface charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] These two opposite surface charges create a net electric field in a direction opposite to the direction of the dipoles.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This idea is given mathematical form using the potential expression above.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In words, the potential due to a constant **p** inside the surface is equivalent to that of a *surface charge* $\sigma =\mathbf {p} \cdot d\mathbf {A}$ which is positive for surface elements with a component in the direction of **p** and negative for surface elements pointed oppositely.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] If the bounding surface is a sphere, and the point of observation is at the center of this sphere, the integration over the surface of the sphere is zero: the positive and negative surface charge contributions to the potential cancel.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] If the point of observation is off-center, however, a net potential can result (depending upon the situation) because the positive and negative charges are at different distances from the point of observation.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] If we suppose the polarization of the dipoles was induced by an external field, the polarization field opposes the applied field and sometimes is called a *depolarization field*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In the case when the polarization is *outside* a spherical cavity, the field in the cavity due to the surrounding dipoles is in the *same* direction as the polarization.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In particular, if the electric susceptibility is introduced through the approximation: $\mathbf {p} (\mathbf {r} )=\varepsilon _{0}\chi (\mathbf {r} )\mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )\,,$ where **E**, in this case and in the following, represent the *external field* which induces the polarization.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Whenever *χ*(**r**) is used to model a step discontinuity at the boundary between two regions, the step produces a surface charge layer.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The right side vanishes as the volume shrinks, inasmuch as *ρ*b is finite, indicating a discontinuity in ***E***, and therefore a surface charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] That is, where the modeled medium includes a step in permittivity, the polarization density corresponding to the dipole moment density $\mathbf {p} (\mathbf {r} )=\varepsilon _{0}\chi (\mathbf {r} )\mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )$ necessarily includes the contribution of a surface charge.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A physically more realistic modeling of **p**(**r**) would have the dipole moment density drop off rapidly, but smoothly to zero at the boundary of the confining region, rather than making a sudden step to zero density.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Then the surface charge will not concentrate in an infinitely thin surface, but instead, being the divergence of a smoothly varying dipole moment density, will distribute itself throughout a thin, but finite transition layer.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The above general remarks about surface charge are made more concrete by considering the example of a dielectric sphere in a uniform electric field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The sphere is found to adopt a surface charge related to the dipole moment of its interior.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The sphere is assumed to be described by a dielectric constant *κ*, that is, $\mathbf {D} =\kappa \varepsilon _{0}\mathbf {E} \,,$ and inside the sphere the potential satisfies Laplace's equation.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Continuity of potential and of the radial component of displacement ***D*** = *κε*0***E*** determine the other two constants.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The factor (*κ* − 1)/(*κ* + 2) is called the Clausius–Mossotti factor and shows that the induced polarization flips sign if *κ* < 1.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Of course, this cannot happen in this example, but in an example with two different dielectrics *κ* is replaced by the ratio of the inner to outer region dielectric constants, which can be greater or smaller than one.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Notice that the field inside the sphere is *uniform* and parallel to the applied field.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipole moment is uniform throughout the interior of the sphere.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This linear dielectric example shows that the dielectric constant treatment is equivalent to the uniform dipole moment model and leads to zero charge everywhere except for the surface charge at the boundary of the sphere.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] If observation is confined to regions sufficiently remote from a system of charges, a multipole expansion of the exact polarization density can be made.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] By truncating this expansion (for example, retaining only the dipole terms, or only the dipole and quadrupole terms, or *etc.*), the results of the previous section are regained.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In particular, truncating the expansion at the dipole term, the result is indistinguishable from the polarization density generated by a uniform dipole moment confined to the charge region.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] To the accuracy of this dipole approximation, as shown in the previous section, the dipole moment *density* **p**(**r**) (which includes not only **p** but the location of **p**) serves as **P**(**r**).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] At locations *inside* the charge array, to connect an array of paired charges to an approximation involving only a dipole moment density **p**(**r**) requires additional considerations.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The simplest approximation is to replace the charge array with a model of ideal (infinitesimally spaced) dipoles.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In particular, as in the example above that uses a constant dipole moment density confined to a finite region, a surface charge and depolarization field results.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A more general version of this model (which allows the polarization to vary with position) is the customary approach using electric susceptibility or electrical permittivity.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A more complex model of the point charge array introduces an effective medium by averaging the microscopic charges; for example, the averaging can arrange that only dipole fields play a role.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] A related approach is to divide the charges into those nearby the point of observation, and those far enough away to allow a multipole expansion.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The nearby charges then give rise to *local field effects*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In a common model of this type, the distant charges are treated as a homogeneous medium using a dielectric constant, and the nearby charges are treated only in a dipole approximation.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The approximation of a medium or an array of charges by only dipoles and their associated dipole moment density is sometimes called the *point dipole* approximation, the *discrete dipole approximation*, or simply the *dipole approximation*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Not to be confused with the magnetic dipole moments of particles, much experimental work is continuing on measuring the electric dipole moments (EDM; or **anomalous electric dipole moment**) of fundamental and composite particles, namely those of the electron and neutron, respectively.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] As EDMs violate both the parity (P) and time-reversal (T) symmetries, their values yield a mostly model-independent measure of CP-violation in nature (assuming CPT symmetry is valid).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Therefore, values for these EDMs place strong constraints upon the scale of CP-violation that extensions to the Standard Model of particle physics may allow.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Current generations of experiments are designed to be sensitive to the supersymmetry range of EDMs, providing complementary experiments to those done at the LHC.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Indeed, many theories are inconsistent with the current limits and have effectively been ruled out, and established theory permits a much larger value than these limits, leading to the strong CP problem and prompting searches for new particles such as the axion.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] We know at least in the Yukawa sector from neutral kaon oscillations that CP is broken.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Experiments have been performed to measure the electric dipole moment of various particles like the electron and the neutron.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Many models beyond the Standard Model with additional CP-violating terms generically predict a nonzero electric dipole moment and are hence sensitive to such new physics.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Instanton corrections from a nonzero *θ* term in quantum chromodynamics predict a nonzero electric dipole moment for the neutron and proton, which have not been observed in experiments (where the best bounds come from analysing neutrons).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This is the strong CP problem and is a prediction of chiral perturbation theory.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Dipole moments in molecules are responsible for the behavior of a substance in the presence of external electric fields.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipoles tend to be aligned to the external field which can be constant or time-dependent.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This effect forms the basis of a modern experimental technique called dielectric spectroscopy.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Dipole moments can be found in common molecules such as water and also in biomolecules such as proteins due to non-uniform distributions of positive and negative charges on the various atoms.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Debye was the first scientist to study electric molecular dipoles extensively, and, as a consequence, dipole moments are measured in the non-SI unit named *debye* in his honor.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] : One atom attracts electrons more than another, becoming more negative, while the other atom becomes more positive.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] These dipoles are smaller in magnitude than permanent dipoles, but still play a large role in chemistry and biochemistry due to their prevalence.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] It is possible to calculate dipole moments from electronic structure theory, either as a response to constant electric fields or from the density matrix.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Such values however are not directly comparable to experiment due to the potential presence of nuclear quantum effects, which can be substantial for even simple systems like the ammonia molecule.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Coupled cluster theory (especially CCSD(T)) can give very accurate dipole moments, although it is possible to get reasonable estimates (within about 5%) from density functional theory, especially if hybrid or double hybrid functionals are employed.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The dipole moment of a molecule can also be calculated based on the molecular structure using the concept of group contribution methods.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] More generally, an induced dipole of *any* polarizable charge distribution *ρ* (remember that a molecule has a charge distribution) is caused by an electric field external to *ρ*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This field may, for instance, originate from an ion or polar molecule in the vicinity of *ρ* or may be macroscopic (e.g., a molecule between the plates of a charged capacitor).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The size of the induced dipole moment is equal to the product of the strength of the external field and the dipole polarizability of *ρ*.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] By means of the total dipole moment of some material one can compute the dielectric constant which is related to the more intuitive concept of conductivity.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Therefore, the dielectric constant (and the conductivity) has contributions from both terms.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This approach can be generalized to compute the frequency dependent dielectric function.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Dipole moment values can be obtained from measurement of the dielectric constant.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Potassium bromide (KBr) has one of the highest dipole moments because it is an ionic compound that exists as a molecule in the gas phase.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] The overall dipole moment of a molecule may be approximated as a vector sum of bond dipole moments.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] As a vector sum it depends on the relative orientation of the bonds, so that from the dipole moment information can be deduced about the molecular geometry.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For example, the zero dipole of CO2 implies that the two C=O bond dipole moments cancel so that the molecule must be linear.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For H2O the O−H bond moments do not cancel because the molecule is bent.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] For ozone (O3) which is also a bent molecule, the bond dipole moments are not zero even though the O−O bonds are between similar atoms.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] This agrees with the Lewis structures for the resonance forms of ozone which show a positive charge on the central oxygen atom.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] An example in organic chemistry of the role of geometry in determining dipole moment is the *cis* and *trans* isomers of 1,2-dichloroethene.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In the *cis* isomer the two polar C−Cl bonds are on the same side of the C=C double bond and the molecular dipole moment is 1.90 D.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] In the *trans* isomer, the dipole moment is zero because the two C−Cl bonds are on opposite sides of the C=C and cancel (and the two bond moments for the much less polar C−H bonds also cancel).
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] Another example of the role of molecular geometry is boron trifluoride, which has three polar bonds with a difference in electronegativity greater than the traditionally cited threshold of 1.7 for ionic bonding.
[src:electrostatics/electric-dipole-moment] However, due to the equilateral triangular distribution of the fluoride ions centered on and in the same plane as the boron cation, the symmetry of the molecule results in its dipole moment being zero.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Since classical antiquity, it has been known that some materials, such as amber, attract lightweight particles after rubbing.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] The Greek word *ḗlektron* (ἤλεκτρον), meaning 'amber', was thus the root of the word *electricity*.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Electrostatic phenomena arise from the forces that electric charges exert on each other.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Such forces are described by Coulomb's law.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] The force is along the straight line joining them.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] If the two charges have the same sign, the electrostatic force between them is repulsive; if they have different signs, the force between them is attractive.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] The electric field, $\mathbf {E}$ , in units of newtons per coulomb or volts per meter, is a vector field that can be defined everywhere, except at the location of point charges (where it diverges to infinity).
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Electric field lines are useful for visualizing the electric field.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Field lines begin on positive charge and terminate on negative charge.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] They are parallel to the direction of the electric field at each point, and the density of these field lines is a measure of the magnitude of the electric field at any given point.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] For a single point charge, q , at the origin, the magnitude of this electric field is $E=q/4\pi \varepsilon _{0}r^{2}$ and points away from that charge if it is positive.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] The fact that the force (and hence the field) can be calculated by summing over all the contributions due to individual source particles is an example of the superposition principle.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Gauss's law states that "the total electric flux through any closed surface in free space of any shape drawn in an electric field is proportional to the total electric charge enclosed by the surface." Many numerical problems can be solved by considering a Gaussian surface around a body.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] where $\mathrm {d} ^{3}r=\mathrm {d} x\ \mathrm {d} y\ \mathrm {d} z$ is a volume element.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] If the charge is distributed over a surface or along a line, replace $\rho \,\mathrm {d} ^{3}r$ by $\sigma \,\mathrm {d} A$ or $\lambda \,\mathrm {d} \ell$ .
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] where $\nabla \cdot$ is the divergence operator.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] This relationship is a form of Poisson's equation.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] If the electric field in a system can be assumed to result from static charges, that is, a system that exhibits no significant time-varying magnetic fields, the system is justifiably analyzed using only the principles of electrostatics.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] This is called the "electrostatic approximation".
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] In other words, electrostatics does not require the absence of magnetic fields or electric currents.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Rather, if magnetic fields or electric currents *do* exist, they must not change with time, or in the worst-case, they must change with time only *very slowly*.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] In some problems, both electrostatics and magnetostatics may be required for accurate predictions, but the coupling between the two can still be ignored.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Electrostatics and magnetostatics can both be seen as non-relativistic Galilean limits for electromagnetism.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] In addition, conventional electrostatics ignore quantum effects which have to be added for a complete description.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] As the electric field is irrotational, it is possible to express the electric field as the gradient of a scalar function, $\phi$ , called the electrostatic potential (also known as the voltage).
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] From these equations, we see that the electric potential is constant in any region for which the electric field vanishes (such as occurs inside a conducting object).
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] A test particle's potential energy, $U_{\mathrm {E} }^{\text{single}}$ , can be calculated from a line integral of the work, $q_{n}\mathbf {E} \cdot \mathrm {d} \mathbf {\ell }$ .
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] We integrate from a point at infinity, and assume a collection of N particles of charge $Q_{n}$ , are already situated at the points $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ .
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] where $\mathbf {\mathcal {R_{i}}} =\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} _{i}$ is the distance of each charge $Q_{i}$ from the test charge q , which situated at the point $\mathbf {r}$ , and $\phi (\mathbf {r} )$ is the electric potential that would be at $\mathbf {r}$ if the test charge were not present.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] If only two charges are present, the potential energy is $Q_{1}Q_{2}/(4\pi \varepsilon _{0}r)$ .
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] This electric potential, $\phi _{i}$ is what would be measured at $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ if the charge $Q_{i}$ were missing.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] This formula obviously excludes the (infinite) energy that would be required to assemble each point charge from a disperse cloud of charge.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] This second expression for electrostatic energy uses the fact that the electric field is the negative gradient of the electric potential, as well as vector calculus identities in a way that resembles integration by parts.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Inside of an electrical conductor, there is no electric field.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] The external electric field has been balanced by surface charges due to movement of charge carriers, either to or from other parts of the material, known as electrostatic induction.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] This pressure acts normal to the surface of the conductor, independent of whether: the mobile charges are electrons, holes or mobile protons; the sign of the surface charge; or the sign of the surface normal component of the electric field.
[src:electrostatics/electrostatics] Note that there is a similar form for electrostriction in a dielectric.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In electromagnetism, the **absolute permittivity**, often simply called **permittivity** and denoted by the Greek letter ε (epsilon), is a measure of the electric polarizability of a dielectric material.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] A material with high permittivity polarizes more in response to an applied electric field than a material with low permittivity, thereby storing more energy in the material.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In electrostatics, the permittivity plays an important role in determining the capacitance of a capacitor.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] More generally, the permittivity is a thermodynamic function of state.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] It can depend on the frequency, magnitude, and direction of the applied field.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The SI unit for permittivity is farad per meter (F/m).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] This dimensionless quantity is also often and ambiguously referred to as the *permittivity*.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Another common term encountered for both absolute and relative permittivity is the *dielectric constant* which has been deprecated in physics and engineering as well as in chemistry.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] By definition, a perfect vacuum has a relative permittivity of exactly 1 whereas at standard temperature and pressure, air has a relative permittivity of εr air ≡ κair ≈ 1.0006 .
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The term "permittivity" was introduced in the 1880s by Oliver Heaviside to complement Thomson's (1872) "permeability".
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Formerly written as p, the designation with ε has been in common use since the 1950s.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The SI unit of permittivity is farad per meter (F/m or F·m−1).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In electromagnetism, the electric displacement field **D** represents the distribution of electric charges in a given medium resulting from the presence of an electric field **E**.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] This distribution includes charge migration and electric dipole reorientation.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] If the medium is anisotropic, the permittivity is a second rank tensor.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In general, permittivity is not a constant, as it can vary with the position in the medium, the frequency of the field applied, humidity, temperature, and other parameters.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In a nonlinear medium, the permittivity can depend on the strength of the electric field.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Permittivity as a function of frequency can take on real or complex values.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In SI units, permittivity is measured in farads per meter (F/m or A2·s4·kg−1·m−3).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The displacement field **D** is measured in units of coulombs per square meter (C/m2), while the electric field **E** is measured in volts per meter (V/m).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] **D** and **E** describe the interaction between charged objects.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] **D** is related to the *charge densities* associated with this interaction, while **E** is related to the *forces* and *potential differences*.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The vacuum permittivity εo (also called **permittivity of free space** or the **electric constant**) is the ratio ⁠*D*/*E*⁠ in free space.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The constants c and µ0 were both defined in SI units to have exact numerical values until the 2019 revision of the SI.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In contrast, the ampere was a measured quantity before 2019, but since then the ampere is now exactly defined and it is μ0 that is an experimentally measured quantity (with consequent uncertainty) and therefore so is the new 2019 definition of ε0 (c remains exactly defined before and since 2019).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The linear permittivity of a homogeneous material is usually given relative to that of free space, as a relative permittivity εr (also called dielectric constant, although this term is deprecated and sometimes only refers to the static, zero-frequency relative permittivity).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In an anisotropic material, the relative permittivity may be a tensor, causing birefringence.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] where χ (frequently written χe) is the electric susceptibility of the material.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] where εo is the electric permittivity of free space.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The susceptibility is also related to the polarizability of individual particles in the medium by the Clausius-Mossotti relation.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The capacitance of a capacitor is based on its design and architecture, meaning it will not change with charging and discharging.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] where A is the area of one plate, d is the distance between the plates, and $\varepsilon$ is the permittivity of the medium between the two plates.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Permittivity is connected to electric flux (and by extension electric field) through Gauss's law.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] $E\ A\ \cos \theta ={\frac {\;Q_{\text{enc}}}{\ \varepsilon _{0}\ }}\ ,$ where $\ \theta \$ represents the angle between the electric field lines and the normal (perpendicular) to S.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] This formula applies to the electric field due to a point charge, outside of a conducting sphere or shell, outside of a uniformly charged insulating sphere, or between the plates of a spherical capacitor.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] That is, the polarization is a convolution of the electric field at previous times with time-dependent susceptibility given by *χ*(Δ*t*).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The upper limit of this integral can be extended to infinity as well if one defines *χ*(Δ*t*) = 0 for Δ*t* < 0.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] An instantaneous response would correspond to a Dirac delta function susceptibility *χ*(Δ*t*) = *χδ*(Δ*t*).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] It is convenient to take the Fourier transform with respect to time and write this relationship as a function of frequency.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] This frequency dependence of the susceptibility leads to frequency dependence of the permittivity.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The shape of the susceptibility with respect to frequency characterizes the dispersion properties of the material.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Moreover, the fact that the polarization can only depend on the electric field at previous times (i.e. effectively *χ*(Δ*t*) = 0 for Δ*t* < 0), a consequence of causality, imposes Kramers–Kronig constraints on the susceptibility *χ*(0).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] As opposed to the response of a vacuum, the response of normal materials to external fields generally depends on the frequency of the field.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] This frequency dependence reflects the fact that a material's polarization does not change instantaneously when an electric field is applied.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The response must always be *causal* (arising after the applied field), which can be represented by a phase difference.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] (since complex numbers allow specification of magnitude and phase).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] At the high-frequency limit (meaning optical frequencies), the complex permittivity is commonly referred to as ε∞ (or sometimes εopt).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] At the plasma frequency and below, dielectrics behave as ideal metals, with electron gas behavior.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The static permittivity is a good approximation for alternating fields of low frequencies, and as the frequency increases a measurable phase difference δ emerges between **D** and **E**.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The frequency at which the phase shift becomes noticeable depends on temperature and the details of the medium.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The choice of sign for time-dependence, e−*iωt*, dictates the sign convention for the imaginary part of permittivity.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The complex permittivity is usually a complicated function of frequency ω, since it is a superimposed description of dispersion phenomena occurring at multiple frequencies.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The dielectric function *ε*(*ω*) must have poles only for frequencies with positive imaginary parts, and therefore satisfies the Kramers–Kronig relations.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] However, in the narrow frequency ranges that are often studied in practice, the permittivity can be approximated as frequency-independent or by model functions.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] At a given frequency, ε″, leads to absorption loss if it is positive (in the above sign convention) and gain if it is negative.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] More generally, the imaginary parts of the eigenvalues of the anisotropic dielectric tensor should be considered.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In the case of solids, the complex dielectric function is intimately connected to band structure.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The primary quantity that characterizes the electronic structure of any crystalline material is the probability of photon absorption, which is directly related to the imaginary part of the optical dielectric function *ε*(*ω*).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In this expression, *W**c*,*v*(*E*) represents the product of the Brillouin zone-averaged transition probability at the energy E with the joint density of states, *J**c*,*v*(*E*); φ is a broadening function, representing the role of scattering in smearing out the energy levels.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In general, the broadening is intermediate between Lorentzian and Gaussian; for an alloy it is somewhat closer to Gaussian because of strong scattering from statistical fluctuations in the local composition on a nanometer scale.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] If ε2 vanishes, then the tensor is diagonal but not proportional to the identity and the medium is said to be a uniaxial medium, which has similar properties to a uniaxial crystal.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Materials can be classified according to their complex-valued permittivity ε, upon comparison of its real *ε*′ and imaginary *ε*″ components (or, equivalently, conductivity, σ, when accounted for in the latter).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Those materials that do not fall under either limit are considered to be general media.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Note that this is using the electrical engineering convention of the complex conjugate ambiguity; the physics/chemistry convention involves the complex conjugate of these equations.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The size of the displacement current is dependent on the frequency ω of the applied field E; there is no displacement current in a constant field.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The above effects often combine to cause non-linear effects within capacitors.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] For example, dielectric absorption refers to the inability of a capacitor that has been charged for a long time to completely discharge when briefly discharged.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Although an ideal capacitor would remain at zero volts after being discharged, real capacitors will develop a small voltage, a phenomenon that is also called *soakage* or *battery action*.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] For some dielectrics, such as many polymer films, the resulting voltage may be less than 1–2% of the original voltage.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] However, it can be as much as 15–25% in the case of electrolytic capacitors or supercapacitors.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In terms of quantum mechanics, permittivity is explained by atomic and molecular interactions.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] At low frequencies, molecules in polar dielectrics are polarized by an applied electric field, which induces periodic rotations.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] For example, at the microwave frequency, the microwave field causes the periodic rotation of water molecules, sufficient to break hydrogen bonds.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The field does work against the bonds and the energy is absorbed by the material as heat.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] This is why microwave ovens work very well for materials containing water.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] There are two maxima of the imaginary component (the absorptive index) of water, one at the microwave frequency, and the other at far ultraviolet (UV) frequency.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Both of these resonances are at higher frequencies than the operating frequency of microwave ovens.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] At moderate frequencies, the energy is too high to cause rotation, yet too low to affect electrons directly, and is absorbed in the form of resonant molecular vibrations.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In water, this is where the absorptive index starts to drop sharply, and the minimum of the imaginary permittivity is at the frequency of blue light (optical regime).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] At high frequencies (such as UV and above), molecules cannot relax, and the energy is purely absorbed by atoms, exciting electron energy levels.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Thus, these frequencies are classified as ionizing radiation.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] While carrying out a complete *ab initio* (that is, first-principles) modelling is now computationally possible, it has not been widely applied yet.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Thus, a phenomenological model is accepted as being an adequate method of capturing experimental behaviors.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The Debye model and the Lorentz model use a first-order and second-order (respectively) lumped system parameter linear representation (such as an RC and an LRC resonant circuit).
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The relative permittivity of a material can be found by a variety of static electrical measurements.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] The complex permittivity is evaluated over a wide range of frequencies by using different variants of dielectric spectroscopy, covering nearly 21 orders of magnitude from 10−6 to 1015 hertz.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Also, by using cryostats and ovens, the dielectric properties of a medium can be characterized over an array of temperatures.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] In order to study systems for such diverse excitation fields, a number of measurement setups are used, each adequate for a special frequency range.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Various microwave measurement techniques are outlined in Chen *et al.* Typical errors for the Hakki–Coleman method employing a puck of material between conducting planes are about 0.3%.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] At infrared and optical frequencies, a common technique is ellipsometry.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] Dual polarisation interferometry is also used to measure the complex refractive index for very thin films at optical frequencies.
[src:electrostatics/permittivity] For the 3D measurement of dielectric tensors at optical frequency, Dielectric tensor tomography can be used.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Poisson's equation is $\Delta \varphi =f,$ where $\Delta$ is the Laplace operator, and f and $\varphi$ are real or complex-valued functions on a manifold.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Usually, f is given, and $\varphi$ is sought.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] When $f=0$ identically, we obtain Laplace's equation.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Poisson's equation may be solved using a Green's function: $\varphi (\mathbf {r} )=-\iiint {\frac {f(\mathbf {r} ')}{4\pi |\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r} '|}}\,\mathrm {d} ^{3}r',$ where the integral is over all of space.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Note here r is where we observe the field, where we are solving for.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] And integrating $r'$ is equivalent to integrating all the "sources".
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] In a sense that we integrate all the effects of sources at $r'$ to get what's seen at r (with the addition of point spread of source).
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] A general exposition of the Green's function for Poisson's equation is given in the article on the screened Poisson equation.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] There are various methods for numerical solution, such as the relaxation method, an iterative algorithm.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] In the case of a gravitational field **g** due to an attracting massive object of density *ρ*, Gauss's law for gravity in differential form can be used to obtain the corresponding Poisson equation for gravity.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] If the mass density is zero, Poisson's equation reduces to Laplace's equation.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The corresponding Green's function can be used to calculate the potential at distance r from a central point mass m (i.e., the fundamental solution).
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] In three dimensions the potential is $\phi (r)={\frac {-Gm}{r}},$ which is equivalent to Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Many problems in electrostatics are governed by the Poisson equation, which relates the electric potential φ to the free charge density $\rho _{f}$ , such as those found in conductors.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The mathematical details of Poisson's equation, commonly expressed in SI units (as opposed to Gaussian units), describe how the distribution of free charges generates the electrostatic potential in a given region.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Assuming the medium is linear, isotropic, and homogeneous (see polarization density), we have the constitutive equation $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon \mathbf {E} ,$ where ε is the permittivity of the medium, and **E** is the electric field.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Then, we have that $\nabla \times \mathbf {E} =0,$ where ∇× is the curl operator.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] This equation means that we can write the electric field as the gradient of a scalar function φ (called the electric potential), since the curl of any gradient is zero.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Thus we can write $\mathbf {E} =-\nabla \varphi ,$ where the minus sign is introduced so that φ is identified as the electric potential energy per unit charge.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The derivation of Poisson's equation under these circumstances is straightforward.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Specifying the Poisson's equation for the potential requires knowing the charge density distribution.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] If the charge density is zero, then Laplace's equation results.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] If the charge density follows a Boltzmann distribution, then the Poisson–Boltzmann equation results.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The Poisson–Boltzmann equation plays a role in the development of the Debye–Hückel theory of dilute electrolyte solutions.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Using a Green's function, the potential at distance r from a central point charge Q (i.e., the fundamental solution) is $\varphi (r)={\frac {Q}{4\pi \varepsilon r}},$ which is Coulomb's law of electrostatics.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The above discussion assumes that the magnetic field is not varying in time.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The same Poisson equation arises even if it does vary in time, as long as the Coulomb gauge is used.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] In this more general class of cases, computing φ is no longer sufficient to calculate **E**, since **E** also depends on the magnetic vector potential **A**, which must be independently computed.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] See Maxwell's equation in potential formulation for more on φ and **A** in Maxwell's equations and how an appropriate Poisson's equation is obtained in this case.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] This solution can be checked explicitly by evaluating ∇2*φ*.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Note that for r much greater than σ, ${\textstyle \operatorname {erf} (r/{\sqrt {2}}\sigma )}$ approaches unity, and the potential *φ*(*r*) approaches the point-charge potential, $\varphi \approx {\frac {1}{4\pi \varepsilon }}{\frac {Q}{r}},$ as one would expect.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Furthermore, the error function approaches 1 extremely quickly as its argument increases; in practice, for *r* > 3.4*σ* the relative error is smaller than one part in a thousand.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Surface reconstruction is an inverse problem.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The goal is to digitally reconstruct a smooth surface based on a large number of points *pi* (a point cloud) where each point also carries an estimate of the local surface normal **n***i*.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Poisson's equation can be utilized to solve this problem with a technique called Poisson surface reconstruction.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The goal of this technique is to reconstruct an implicit function *f* whose value is zero at the points *pi* and whose gradient at the points *pi* equals the normal vectors **n***i*.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The set of (*pi*, **n***i*) is thus modeled as a continuous vector field **V**.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The implicit function *f* is found by integrating the vector field **V**.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Since not every vector field is the gradient of a function, the problem may or may not have a solution: the necessary and sufficient condition for a smooth vector field **V** to be the gradient of a function *f* is that the curl of **V** must be identically zero.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] In case this condition is difficult to impose, it is still possible to perform a least-squares fit to minimize the difference between **V** and the gradient of *f*.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] In order to effectively apply Poisson's equation to the problem of surface reconstruction, it is necessary to find a good discretization of the vector field **V**.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The basic approach is to bound the data with a finite-difference grid.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] For a function valued at the nodes of such a grid, its gradient can be represented as valued on staggered grids, i.e. on grids whose nodes lie in between the nodes of the original grid.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] It is convenient to define three staggered grids, each shifted in one and only one direction corresponding to the components of the normal data.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] On each staggered grid we perform trilinear interpolation on the set of points.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] The interpolation weights are then used to distribute the magnitude of the associated component of *ni* onto the nodes of the particular staggered grid cell containing *pi*.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Kazhdan and coauthors give a more accurate method of discretization using an adaptive finite-difference grid, i.e. the cells of the grid are smaller (the grid is more finely divided) where there are more data points.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] They suggest implementing this technique with an adaptive octree.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] Thermal conduction is modelled via the Heat equation.
[src:electrostatics/poisson-s-equation] where $\vartheta$ is the temperature, $\Phi$ is the heat source term and $\lambda$ is Thermal conductivity.
